# Funky Sampler Code for Use in 1.2
funkySampler <- function(dataset, size, n){
    results <- numeric(n)
    for(i in 1:n){
        vectorSample <- sample(dataset, size)
        results[i] <- mean(vectorSample)
    }
    return(results)
}

library('seqinr')
dengue <- read.fasta(file = 'dengue_seq.txt')
dengue_vec <- as.vector(dengue[[1]])

GC_content <- function(seq){
  length <- 0
  c <- 0
  g <- 0
  
for(i in seq){
  length <- length + 1
  if(i=="c"){
    c <- c+1
  }
  if(i=="g"){
    g <- g+1
  }
}
  GC_content <- ((g+c)/length)*100
  return(GC_content)
}

findGC <- function(dataset, size, n){
    results <- numeric(n)
    for(i in 1:n){
        vectorSample <- sample(dataset, size)
        results[i] <- GC_content(vectorSample)
    }
    return(results)
}


findGC(dengue_vec, 100, 10)
##  [1] 44 50 45 58 43 50 51 49 50 46

3.1 (a) 97.5 is calculated because we take the 5% (100 - 95 = 5) and divide it by two, and then put the 2.5% at either ends of the interval, so that its 2.5 97.5 2.5. The qnorm(0.975) yields a two sided confidence interval.

3.1 (b) Using CI formula, we can use qnorm(0.975) as the z value, and +/- the error from the calculated mean in order to find the CI. Ater subtracting 0.025 from either side of the curve, we will get the 95%.

3.1 (c) qnorm(0.95) is used since we subtract 0.05 from either side of the curve.

3.2

CI95 <- function(data){
error <- qnorm(0.975) * sd(data) / sqrt(length(data)) 
lower <- round(mean(data) - error, digits = 2)
upper <- round(mean(data) + error, digits = 2)

CI95 <- paste(toString(lower), ",", toString(upper))
return(CI95)
}

3.3 (a)

vec1 <- runif(8500, 0, 1)
vec2 <- rnorm(8500, 15)

3.3 (b)

hist(vec1, col = "red")

hist(vec2, col = "blue")

3.3 (c)

CV_1 <- (sd(vec1)/mean(vec1))*100
CV_1
## [1] 57.50479
CV_2 <- (sd(vec2)/mean(vec2))*100
CV_2
## [1] 6.707985

THe CV of vec1 was much larger than the one for vec2 because vec1 has a uniform distribution, so each of the values have relatively similar probabilities. There are more values that deviate from the mean. vec2 is normally distributed, so the values to the center of the distribution have a higher probability so the ones further from the center are less likely/have a lower probability. The standard deviation for normal distributions is smaller and the standard deviation for uniform distribution is larger.

5.4

bernoulli <- function(flips, trials){
    result <- numeric(trials)
    for(i in 1:trials){
        tot_head <- sum(round(runif(flips)))
        result[i] <- tot_head/(flips)
    }
    return(result)
}

bernoulli(20,9)
## [1] 0.45 0.60 0.45 0.40 0.55 0.35 0.60 0.45 0.40
